# Frontend Domain Rules

> **Note**: Customize this template for your frontend framework. Examples use React/TypeScript, but adapt to Vue, Svelte, Angular, etc.

## COMPONENT STRUCTURE

### Organization

```tsx
// Related to: TASK-XXX - [Task Title]
// PRD: docs/prd/[feature-name]-prd.md

import React from 'react';
import { SomeHook } from './hooks';

// Props interface at top
interface ComponentProps {
  title: string;
  onAction: () => void;
}

// Functional component
export const Component: React.FC<ComponentProps> = ({ title, onAction }) => {
  // Hooks before render logic
  const [state, setState] = useState();
  const data = useCustomHook();

  // Render logic
  return (
    <div>
      {/* Component JSX */}
    </div>
  );
};

// Helper functions after component
const helperFunction = () => {
  // ...
};
```

### Best Practices

- **Component Size**: Max 300 lines per component
- **Reusability**: Extract reusable logic to custom hooks
- **Styling**: Use styled-components, CSS modules, or Tailwind
- **State Management**: Use appropriate tool (Context, Redux, Zustand)
- **Type Safety**: Use TypeScript for type safety

## ACCESSIBILITY

- Use semantic HTML elements
- Add ARIA labels where needed
- Ensure keyboard navigation works
- Maintain proper focus management
- Test with screen readers
- Ensure color contrast meets WCAG standards

## ERROR HANDLING

- Use error boundaries for component error handling
- Display user-friendly error messages
- Log errors appropriately
- Handle loading states
- Handle empty states gracefully

## PERFORMANCE

- Use React.memo for expensive components
- Lazy load routes and heavy components
- Optimize images (use next/image or similar)
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders
- Use useMemo/useCallback appropriately
- Code split large bundles

## STATE MANAGEMENT

- Keep state as local as possible
- Lift state up only when necessary
- Use Context for theme/auth/global state
- Consider state management library for complex apps
- Avoid prop drilling (use Context or state management)

## TESTING

- Test user interactions, not implementation
- Test accessibility
- Test error states
- Test loading states
- Use React Testing Library
- Test component behavior, not internals

## STYLING

- Use consistent design system
- Follow mobile-first approach
- Ensure responsive design
- Use CSS variables for theming
- Maintain consistent spacing/typography

## CODE QUALITY

- Extract reusable components
- Keep components focused (single responsibility)
- Use meaningful variable names
- Add comments for complex logic
- Follow project's ESLint/Prettier config
- Use TypeScript strictly (no `any` types)

## USER EXPERIENCE

- Show loading indicators
- Provide feedback for user actions
- Handle edge cases gracefully
- Ensure smooth transitions/animations
- Optimize for mobile devices
- Test across browsers
